item.title: Obama Begins Visit to Israel
item.description: The president arrived in Tel Aviv at the start of a long-awaited three-day trip to the Middle East in which he will directly address the Israeli people.

item.title: Osborne Warns of Skidding Economy
item.description: U.K. Treasury chief George Osborne said growth would be much slower than expected and his government would have to borrow almost $90.6 billion more than planned, which is likely to fuel criticism of his austerity drive.

item.title: Cyprus Rejects Rescue Plan
item.description: Cyprus's parliament voted down the bailout deal the country had negotiated just days earlier with European and international creditors.

item.title: Ball Now in Cyprus's Court, Says EU
item.description: After rejecting the bailout plan and its controversial levy on bank savings, Cyprus has now to come up with its own alternative, the European Commission says.

item.title: Cyprus-Russia Talks Show Little Progress
item.description: Cyprus's attempt to secure much-needed financial aid from Russia showed little sign of progress as the embattled island nation's finance minister came away apparently empty-handed from meetings with Russian ministers.

item.title: Lew Presses China on Cybersecurity
item.description: U.S. Treasury Secretary Jacob Lew wrapped up two days of meetings here with China's new leaders, in which the two sides discussed currency issues, cybersecurity and economic reform.

item.title: EU Warns India on Italian Envoy
item.description: The European Union said India would violate international law if it stopped the Italian ambassador in New Delhi from leaving the country, throwing its weight behind Rome amid an intensifying diplomatic row.

item.title: South Korea Investigates Cyberattack
item.description: South Korean police are investigating one of the country's biggest Internet shutdowns for evidence of a North Korean cyberattack, after outages paralyzed computer systems at TV networks and banks.

item.title: U.S. Agrees to Provincial Pullout in Afghanistan
item.description: The U.S.-led coalition said it will begin pulling Special Operations forces from the Afghan province of Wardak, satisfying President Hamid Karzai's demand and removing an irritant in relations.

item.title: Blasts Hit Turkish Government Offices
item.description: Turkish government and ruling party offices have been rocked by a series of bomb attacks, marking what government ministers say could be a violent effort to derail peace talks to end a three-decade Kurdish insurgency.

item.title: Swiss to Vote on Executive Pay
item.description: Switzerland is expected to vote later this year on a proposal to impose further limits on executive pay, the latest effort to govern compensation in a country that recently approved some of the world's strictest say-on-pay rules.

item.title: India Coalition Says Government Stable
item.description: India's government said it was 'absolutely stable' despite the withdrawal of support by the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party, and that its agenda of policy reforms and legislative business will not be affected by the party's exit.

item.title: Wave of Deadly Attacks Hits Baghdad
item.description: Dozens of Iraqis were killed or wounded in a barrage of car bombs on the eve of the 10th anniversary of the start of the U.S.-led invasion.

item.title: Militant Tied to Pearl Death Is Arrested
item.description: Pakistani authorities arrested a militant who they say was connected with the murder of Wall Street Journal reporter Daniel Pearl in 2002.

item.title: Syria Alleges Rebels Launched Chemical Attack
item.description: Syria's government accused rebels of firing a chemical weapon Tuesday, levying the first such allegation against the rebel insurgency in two years of fighting and setting governments on edge from Moscow to Washington.

item.title: As Virus Spreads, Saudis Defend Role
item.description: A SARS-like virus has infected 15 people, nine of whom have died, mostly in Saudi Arabia, worrying some Western scientists who question whether the kingdom is sharing enough critical data on the outbreak.

item.title: Russia Drops Whistleblower Death Case
item.description: Russia's top law-enforcement body dropped its investigation into the 2009 death in a Moscow jail of Sergei Magnitsky, a whistleblower attorney.

item.title: Earthquake Traps Miners in Poland
item.description: A magnitude 4.7 earthquake in southwestern Poland trapped 17 miners underground late Tuesday, copper miner KGHM Polska Miedz SA said.

item.title: Bahrain Torture Claims Prompt Call for Probe
item.description: Five detainees arrested in Bahrain last year said they were tortured in custody, accusations that a member of an official inquiry panel said should be formally investigated.

item.title: Zimbabwe Passes New Constitution
item.description: Zimbabwe's election commission said voters gave near-unanimous approval of a new constitution, a victory for two bitter political rivals that paves the way for them to compete again in national elections this year.

item.title: U.K. Press Regulation Faces Hurdles
item.description: An agreement by Britain's three main political parties on how to regulate the press faced the challenge of how to get the country's newspapers on board with the plan.

item.title: Canada Firm Places Bet on Mexico Border
item.description: In Ciudad Juárez, Mexico, Brookfield Asset Management is betting that it can put together the pieces of an investment that was undercut by the U.S. recession and drug wars.

item.title: Mexico Considers Opening Its Waters
item.description: As Mexico marks 75 years since it expropriated oil assets, the government is considering how to attract private investment. But a history of false starts has made a lot of skeptics.

item.title: India Party Pulls Government Support
item.description: A key member of India's ruling coalition walked out of the government in a move that is unlikely to pull down Prime Minister Manmohan Singh's administration but will lead to political uncertainty.

item.title: Banned Mutton Found in Horse Meat Probe
item.description: French authorities have discovered banned mutton at the French company at the heart of Europe's horse meat scandal, fueling concerns about food safety controls.

item.title: Philippines Reproductive Health Law on Hold
item.description: The Philippine Supreme Court ordered the government to suspend the implementation of a recently passed reproductive health law aimed at slowing the Southeast Asian nation's population growth.

item.title: French Minister Quits Amid Probe
item.description: France's budget minister stepped down after French prosecutors said they had launched an probe into allegations of money laundering and tax evasion.

item.title: Venezuela Acts to Ease Dollar Shortage
item.description: Venezuela moved to get more dollars into importers' hands to curb growing shortages of basic goods and tame a runaway currency black market by creating a complementary foreign-exchange agency that will auction greenbacks.

item.title: Italy Issues Public-Spending Review
item.description: Italy's technocrat administration issued a long-awaited analytical report on how to cut public spending.

item.title: India Cabinet Clears Food-Security Bill
item.description: India's federal cabinet cleared an ambitious food security bill that would allow 67% of the population access to cheap food grains.

item.title: India Bus Crash Kills Dozens
item.description: A bus packed with passengers crashed through a guard rail and fell off a bridge in western India early Tuesday, killing at least 37 people.

item.title: Belgian Train Museum Had a Hard Time Getting on Track
item.description: The latest problem for this train-mad country: too many historic steam engines.

item.title: Afghan Church Endures
item.description: Inside Italy's embassy, a Catholic priest operates Afghanistan's only church.

item.title: Focus on Survival in Syrian Capital
item.description: For most residents in the Syrian capital, war governs every detail of life. Damascus residents, whether they are opponents and supporters of the regime, have honed their survival skills.

item.title: Beijing's Spring Snowfall
item.description: Beijing residents woke up Wednesday, the first official day of spring in the Chinese traditional calendar, to a city blanketed in white after an overnight snow storm.

item.title: Wu Led Village to Become China's Richest
item.description: Wu Renbao, who used "capitalism with Chinese characteristics" to turn a farm community into what is now known in China as the country's richest village, died of lung cancer.

item.title: Diana's Million-Dollar Wardrobe
item.description: Kerry Taylor Auctions expects to raise more than £800,000 pounds ($1.2 million) with the sale of 10 dresses belonging to Britain's late Princess Diana, which are up for auction Tuesday.
